---
<SiteLayout site="firemaths" title="What is Coast FIRE? Calculator and Complete Guide" description="Learn what Coast FIRE is, calculate your Coast FI number, and discover how this financial milestone can change your life today." canonical="https://firemaths.info/what-is-coast-fire" schema={schema}>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>What is Coast FIRE?</h1>
      <p>The milestone where saving for retirement is optional, and compound interest takes the wheel.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="card calc-card">
      <h3 style="margin-top:0">Coast FIRE Calculator</h3>
      <div class="input-group">
        <label>Current Age</label>
        <input type="number" id="currentAge" value="30" />
      </div>
      <div class="input-group">
        <label>Retirement Age</label>
        <input type="number" id="retirementAge" value="65" />
      </div>
      <div class="input-group">
        <label>Annual Expenses in Retirement ($)</label>
        <input type="number" id="annualExpenses" value="40000" />
      </div>
      <div class="input-group">
        <label>Assumed Real Return Rate (%)</label>
        <input type="number" id="returnRate" value="6" step="0.1" />
      </div>
      <button onclick="calculateCoastFire()">Calculate Coast FI Number</button>

      <div class="results" id="calcResults" style="display:none;">
        <div class="result-row">
          <span>Target FIRE Number (25x expenses):</span>
          <span id="targetFi" class="value"></span>
        </div>
        <div class="result-row total">
          <span>Your Coast FIRE Number:</span>
          <span id="coastFi" class="value highlight"></span>
        </div>
        <p class="result-desc">If you have <strong id="descAmt"></strong> invested by age <span id="descAge"></span>, you never need to invest another penny for retirement.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="article-content">

      <h2>Understanding the Concept of Coast FIRE</h2>
      <p>The journey to Financial Independence and Early Retirement (FIRE) can often feel like a massive, uphill battle. Saving 25 times your annual expenses requires immense discipline and a high savings rate. But what if there was a milestone along the way that allowed you to take your foot off the gas? Enter <strong>Coast FIRE</strong>.</p>

      <p>Coast FIRE (or Coast FI) is a financial milestone where you have saved enough money early in life that, without any additional contributions, your investments will grow to reach your traditional FIRE number by a standard retirement age (usually 65).</p>

      <p>Once you hit this milestone, you are "coasting." The heavy lifting of saving for retirement is done. You no longer need to save a portion of your income for the future. From that point on, you only need to earn enough money to cover your current living expenses.</p>

      <h3>The Math Behind Coast FIRE</h3>
      <p>To understand how Coast FIRE works, you need to understand compound interest. When you invest money, it earns a return. The next year, you earn a return on both your original investment and the previous year's return. Over decades, this compounding effect is incredibly powerful.</p>

      <p>The Coast FIRE formula works backward from your ultimate FIRE goal. Here are the steps:</p>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Determine your FIRE number:</strong> This is typically 25 times your expected annual expenses in retirement (based on the 4% rule).</li>
        <li><strong>Determine the time horizon:</strong> Calculate the number of years between your current age and your traditional retirement age.</li>
        <li><strong>Assume a real rate of return:</strong> Choose a conservative estimate for your investments' annual growth after inflation (commonly 5% to 7%).</li>
        <li><strong>Discount your FIRE number:</strong> Calculate the present value of your FIRE number using the time horizon and assumed return rate.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Real-World Coast FIRE Example</h3>
      <p>Let's look at a concrete example to make this clearer.</p>
      <p>Meet Sarah. She is 30 years old. She expects to spend $40,000 per year in retirement.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Sarah's FIRE Number:</strong> $40,000 x 25 = $1,000,000</li>
        <li><strong>Traditional Retirement Age:</strong> 65</li>
        <li><strong>Years to Grow:</strong> 35 years (65 - 30)</li>
        <li><strong>Assumed Real Return:</strong> 6%</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Using the present value formula, Sarah's Coast FIRE number at age 30 is approximately <strong>$130,105</strong>.</p>
      <p>If Sarah has $130,105 invested at age 30, and she never invests another penny, that money will grow (at an average real return of 6%) to $1,000,000 by the time she is 65. Sarah is Coast FIRE.</p>

      <h3>Why Aim for Coast FIRE?</h3>
      <p>Reaching Coast FIRE fundamentally changes your relationship with work. While you still need to work to cover your daily expenses, the intense pressure to save is gone. This opens up incredible lifestyle options:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Downshifting:</strong> You can take a lower-paying, lower-stress job that you actually enjoy.</li>
        <li><strong>Part-time work:</strong> You could reduce your hours to 3 or 4 days a week.</li>
        <li><strong>Entrepreneurship:</strong> You can take the risk of starting a business, knowing your retirement is secure even if the business only covers your living expenses.</li>
        <li><strong>Career breaks:</strong> You have the flexibility to take mini-retirements or sabbaticals.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Coast FIRE vs. Barista FIRE vs. Lean FIRE</h3>
      <p>It's important to distinguish Coast FIRE from other popular FIRE strategies:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Coast FIRE:</strong> You must earn enough to cover 100% of your current expenses. Your investments are untouched and growing.</li>
        <li><strong><a href="/what-is-barista-fire">Barista FIRE</a>:</strong> Your investments are large enough to cover *some* of your expenses, so you work a part-time job (often for health benefits) to cover the rest.</li>
        <li><strong><a href="/what-is-lean-fire">Lean FIRE</a>:</strong> You have enough invested to completely stop working, but you are living on a minimalist budget (typically under $40,000/year).</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>How to Reach Coast FIRE Faster</h3>
      <p>If you want to hit this milestone as quickly as possible, focus on these three levers:</p>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Start early:</strong> Time is the most critical factor. The earlier you invest, the longer compound interest can work its magic, and the lower your Coast FI number will be.</li>
        <li><strong>Increase your savings rate:</strong> Maximize your <a href="/what-is-savings-rate">savings rate</a> in your early earning years. House hacking, geographic arbitrage, and side hustles can help boost this.</li>
        <li><strong>Lower your future expenses:</strong> If you can learn to be happy spending less, your ultimate FI number drops, which drastically reduces your Coast FI number.</li>
      </ol>

      <p>To deepen your understanding of these concepts, be sure to review our <a href="/fire-dictionary">Complete FIRE Dictionary</a>.</p>

    </div>

    <div class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="card faq-card">
        <h3>What is the difference between Coast FIRE and regular FIRE?</h3>
        <p>Regular FIRE requires saving until you have enough invested to cover all your expenses without working. Coast FIRE means you have saved enough early on that your investments will grow to reach your FIRE number by traditional retirement age, without needing to add another dime.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card faq-card">
        <h3>How is the Coast FIRE number calculated?</h3>
        <p>Your Coast FIRE number is your final FIRE number (usually 25x annual expenses) discounted back to your current age using an assumed real rate of return (often 5% to 7% after inflation).</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card faq-card">
        <h3>Does Coast FIRE mean I can stop working entirely?</h3>
        <p>No. Once you reach Coast FIRE, you no longer need to contribute to retirement savings, but you still need to earn enough to cover your current living expenses until you reach traditional retirement age.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <script is:inline>
    function calculateCoastFire() {
      const currentAge = parseFloat(document.getElementById('currentAge').value);
      const retirementAge = parseFloat(document.getElementById('retirementAge').value);
      const annualExpenses = parseFloat(document.getElementById('annualExpenses').value);
      const returnRate = parseFloat(document.getElementById('returnRate').value) / 100;

      if (isNaN(currentAge) || isNaN(retirementAge) || isNaN(annualExpenses) || isNaN(returnRate)) return;
      if (currentAge >= retirementAge) {
        alert("Current age must be less than retirement age.");
        return;
      }

      const targetFi = annualExpenses * 25;
      const yearsToGrow = retirementAge - currentAge;

      // PV = FV / (1 + r)^t
      const coastFi = targetFi / Math.pow((1 + returnRate), yearsToGrow);

      const formatter = new Intl.NumberFormat('en-US', { style: 'currency', currency: 'USD', maximumFractionDigits: 0 });

      document.getElementById('targetFi').innerText = formatter.format(targetFi);
      document.getElementById('coastFi').innerText = formatter.format(coastFi);
      document.getElementById('descAmt').innerText = formatter.format(coastFi);
      document.getElementById('descAge').innerText = currentAge;

      document.getElementById('calcResults').style.display = 'block';
    }
  </script>
